System requirements
-------------------

To build Captool you need the following software installed on your system
(corresponding Debian package names used by Captool authors are given in 
parentheses):

- C++ compiler (g++ >= 4.3 for <unordered_map> or Boost equivalent)
- Boost C++ Libraries, with development headers (libboost-dev, 
  libboost-system-dev)
- libconfig C/C++ Configuration File Library, C++ version with headers
  (libconfig++-dev;  on Ubuntu libconfig-dev too)
- libxml++2.6-dev
- pkg-config
- libpcre3-dev
- libpcap-dev

Minimum package versions are not given because the lack of extensive test
on our part---please feel free to try the current stable versions in your
distribution.


Installing from source
----------------------

If the above system requirements are satisfied, you can try the following to
build Captool::

  svn co https://teamforge.lmera.ericsson.se/svn/repos/captool/trunk/captool
  cd captool
  ./configure
  make
  make install

Optional switches to ``./configure`` above::

  --prefix=PFX             installation directory prefix (default: same directory
                           where `configure' is run)
  --enable-debug           compile with debug symbols (default: disabled)
  --enable-profile         compile a profiling `captool' binary (default: disabled)
  --enable-static          compile a statically linked binary (default: disabled)
  --enable-profile[=perftools]
                          Build profiling binary (standard or
                          `google-perftools') [default no; implies
                          --enable-static']
  --with-boost-asio[=special-lib]
                          use the ASIO library from boost - it is possible to
                          specify a certain library for the linker e.g.
                          --with-boost-asio=boost_system-mt

Note for Ubuntu build you **have** to specify
``--with-boost-asio=boost_system-mt``.

Profiling build optionally supports Google Performance Tools
(libgoogle-perftools-dev), by adding the ``--enable-profile=perftools``
switch.
